<P>In the play of the Fair Penitent, Lothario is killed by Altamont in the fourth act. His corp&s;e is &s;uppo&s;ed to be exhibited in that di&s;mal &s;cene which opens the fifth act of the play, where poor Cali&s;ta is &s;urrounded by chaple&s;s &s;kulls, bones, and every object that can excite repentance, contrition and horror. The &s;upporting the dig|nity of this character generally falls to one of the lowe&s;t cla&s;s in the theatre. Booth acted Lothario, and his footman Will was his dead re|pre&s;entative. This great actor, who was &s;ome|times &s;ubject to ab&s;ence of mind, remembered when he was undre&s;&s;ed, that he wanted his &s;er|vant to attend him ho$$e, and called out loudly, "Will! where are you?" Will heard his ma|&s;ter's voice, and an&s;wered as loudly, "Here, Sir! I am coming;" and marched off with the &s;hroud upon his back, amid&s;t the loude&s;t applau|&s;es that were ever heard in the theatre. Even Mrs. Oldfield, who was the Cali&s;ta, was in&s;en&s;i|bly drawn into a &s;mile, and the play ended im|mediately with repeated bur&s;ts of laughter.</P>
<P>The celebrated Mr. Quin, who was a great
